This paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category as it proposes a multileader Paxos protocol that provides consensus across wide-area network (WAN) deployments. It also mentions the use of object stealing to adapt to changing access locality, which is a common problem in distributed computing. 

The paper could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category as it proposes a novel approach to achieving fast phase-2 commits using flexible quorums. 

The Operating Systems (cs.OS) sub-category is also a possibility as the paper discusses the implementation of WPaxos and its evaluation on WAN deployments across 5 AWS regions. 

The Networked and Internet Systems (cs.NI) sub-category is another possibility as the paper focuses on achieving low-latency and high-throughput consensus across wide-area network (WAN) deployments. 

Finally, the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category is a possibility as the paper proposes a protocol for achieving consensus in distributed systems, which is a common problem in control systems.
